Now Martial, addressing his fourth book, advises it to gain the approval of Apollinaris, and tells it, if condemned, to be off to the trunk-makers’ :

si damnaverit, ad salariorum curras scrinia protinus licebitss.

The words are almost exactly those of Catullus 3 the mean- ing is entirely different. There can be no stronger proof of ingrained familiarity than such unconscious imitation.

The following is a list of the passages in the Eclogues and Georgics which are most obviously imitated from the fifth book of Lucretius.
